{"title":"Turbidity Time Series with UK PCV Limit","analysis_comments":"Turbidity results across 2022 are generally low, with the bulk of samples between ~0.05–0.4 NTU. The regulatory PCV of 1 NTU is plotted as a red dashed line; exceedances above this level are infrequent and scattered through the year.

There is no clear seasonal trend, but occasional peaks approach or slightly exceed 1 NTU, including isolated values above 1.4 NTU and a single outlier near 2.7 NTU. These likely reflect localised distribution disturbances, short-lived treatment upsets, or sampling artefacts rather than systematic problems.

Given the overall low baseline and sparse failures, compliance is good. However, the outliers warrant correlation with operational events (e.g. mains flushing, bursts, filter backwashing) and location data (LSOA) to confirm they were transient and to check if any specific zones are recurrently affected.","chart_filename":"turbidity_timeseries.png","chart_html_filename":"turbidity_timeseries.html","code_filename":"turbidity_timeseries.py","data_filename":"turbidity_timeseries_data.csv"}

{"title":"Coliform Bacteria Time Series (All Results vs Zero PCV)","analysis_comments":"Coliform bacteria results are dominated by zeros throughout 2022, with relatively few positive values. Non‑zero results occur sporadically across the year rather than clustering in a single season.

Most positives are low-level (1–5 per 100 ml), but there are several pronounced spikes, notably in March (up to ~95/100 ml) and further events in late summer and autumn with results in the 20–55/100 ml range. These outliers likely correspond to discrete contamination or sampling events at specific properties or small zones.

Given the regulatory PCV of 0 per 100 ml, every non‑zero value is a failure, so each spike warrants local investigation. Linking these timestamps with LSOA and Sample_Id in the CSV would help distinguish repeated problem areas from isolated occurrences and check for any association with network operations or supply changes.","chart_filename":"coliform_timeseries.png","chart_html_filename":"coliform_timeseries.html","code_filename":"coliform_timeseries.py","data_filename":"coliform_timeseries_data.csv"}

{"title":"E. coli Time Series (All Results vs Zero PCV)","analysis_comments":"E. coli results are overwhelmingly zero throughout 2022, aligning well with the PCV of 0 number/100 ml. Only a handful of non‑zero results are visible against the x‑axis, with three clear spikes: one small event (~1/100 ml) in late February, a moderate event (~9/100 ml) in early June, and a major event (~90/100 ml) around late March.

These isolated exceedances suggest rare but significant contamination incidents rather than systematic treatment failure. Each spike represents non‑compliance at the individual sample level and would warrant local investigation—checking sampling conditions, plumbing at the premises, and any concurrent operational disturbances.

Given the low frequency compared with the total number of E. coli samples, overall microbiological performance is strong, but the March high outlier is particularly important to review in incident records.","chart_filename":"ecoli_timeseries.png","chart_html_filename":"ecoli_timeseries.html","code_filename":"ecoli_timeseries.py","data_filename":"ecoli_timeseries_data.csv"}

{"title":"Aluminium Time Series with UK PCV Limit","analysis_comments":"Aluminium concentrations are generally well below the 200 µg/L PCV, with most results under ~30 µg/L. However, there is a pronounced period of elevated aluminium from roughly March to July 2022, with frequent values between 40–150 µg/L and several peaks above 150 µg/L.

Only a small number of samples approach or exceed the 200 µg/L limit; the highest outlier is just above 250 µg/L in mid‑summer. After August, levels stabilise close to baseline, rarely exceeding ~20 µg/L.

The temporal clustering of elevated results suggests process‑related issues (e.g. sub‑optimal coagulation, filter performance, or aluminium carry‑over) during that mid‑year period rather than persistent distribution problems. Correlating these dates with works at the supplying works and affected LSOAs would help pinpoint root causes and confirm that remedial actions taken after summer were effective.","chart_filename":"aluminium_timeseries.png","chart_html_filename":"aluminium_timeseries.html","code_filename":"aluminium_timeseries.py","data_filename":"aluminium_timeseries_data.csv"}

{"title":"Iron Time Series with UK PCV Limit","analysis_comments":"Iron concentrations are mostly low, typically below ~80 µg/L, and many samples sit under 20 µg/L. The PCV of 200 µg/L is shown as a dashed red line; exceedances above this level are rare.

There are intermittent higher iron events across the year, including clusters around May–June, August, and November–December, with values up to ~350 µg/L. One extreme outlier in late summer exceeds 1,400 µg/L, far above the standard and clearly visible against the baseline.

The sporadic nature and magnitude of these peaks suggest localised distribution or point‑source issues (e.g. mains disturbance, old iron pipework, or storage tank sediment mobilisation) rather than chronically high iron from treatment works. Correlating these dates with LSOA and operational events would help target flushing or asset interventions where repeated spikes occur.","chart_filename":"iron_timeseries.png","chart_html_filename":"iron_timeseries.html","code_filename":"iron_timeseries.py","data_filename":"iron_timeseries_data.csv"}

{"title":"Manganese Time Series with UK PCV Limit","analysis_comments":"Manganese levels are mostly low, with the majority of samples between ~0.5–6 µg/L and well below the 50 µg/L PCV. The red dashed PCV line clearly shows that exceedances are very rare.

There are a few notable peaks: a single extreme value around late June–July (~185 µg/L) and another high result near early August (~125 µg/L). A small cluster of moderate elevations (10–25 µg/L) appears in late summer to early autumn, but these still sit comfortably below the PCV.

The isolated high spikes likely reflect local distribution disturbances or specific asset issues (e.g. deposits mobilised in low‑turnover mains or service reservoirs). Given the low baseline, these events merit targeted investigation at the affected LSOAs but do not indicate a systemic manganese problem in the wider supply.","chart_filename":"manganese_timeseries.png","chart_html_filename":"manganese_timeseries.html","code_filename":"manganese_timeseries.py","data_filename":"manganese_timeseries_data.csv"}

{"title":"Enterococci Time Series (All Results vs Zero PCV)","analysis_comments":"Enterococci monitoring results are almost entirely compliant, with all but a single sample at 0 number/100 ml across 2022. One isolated non‑zero result of 1/100 ml occurs around early September.

Given the PCV of 0 per 100 ml, this single detection constitutes a failure at the sample level but is very low in magnitude and not accompanied by repeated events before or after. This pattern suggests a sporadic contamination or sampling artefact rather than an underlying distribution or treatment issue.

Because enterococci are used as an indicator of faecal contamination, it would still be appropriate to review this particular incident in context—checking co‑located E. coli and coliform results, the LSOA and premises characteristics, and any operational disturbances on that date.","chart_filename":"enterococci_timeseries.png","chart_html_filename":"enterococci_timeseries.html","code_filename":"enterococci_timeseries.py","data_filename":"enterococci_timeseries_data.csv"}

{"title":"Gross Alpha Time Series with Screening Value Limit","analysis_comments":"Gross alpha activity is consistently low across 2022 for the two monitored LSOAs. Eight of nine samples lie between 0.02 and 0.053 Bq/L, comfortably below the 0.1 Bq/L screening value. A single sample on 25 January 2022 at LSOA E01017616 reaches 0.152 Bq/L, exceeding the screening threshold.

Under the Regulations this exceedance does not automatically imply non‑compliance with the 0.1 mSv indicative dose, but it triggers the requirement to investigate radionuclide composition. Follow‑up sampling and analysis for specific alpha‑emitting radionuclides would be expected around that supply point.

The absence of further elevated results later in the year suggests this was a transient or localised issue rather than a persistent radiological problem in the wider network.","chart_filename":"grossalpha_timeseries.png","chart_html_filename":"grossalpha_timeseries.html","code_filename":"grossalpha_timeseries.py","data_filename":"grossalpha_timeseries_data.csv"}
